Rationale for classification: Although a potential of stimulating the skin slightly as effect of short-term exposure to humans is suggested (HSDB (Access on Oct 2005), HSFS (2004) and ICSC (J) (2000)), there is no case reports. On the other hand, there was description that irritation was not admitted by the test which used the rabbit (IUCLID (2000), HSDB (Access on Oct 2005)). So it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: tert-Butyl 4-({[(1,3-dimethyl-5-phenoxy-4-pyrazolyl)methylidene]aminooxy}methyl)benzoate; Fenpyroximate
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2002)): Non-irritating to the skin.

Name: 2-Propanol, 1-(2-methoxypropoxy)- ; Dipropylene Glycol Methyl Ether
Rationale for classification: From description that irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the skin of the rabbit (ACGIH (7th, 2001) and SIDS (2001)), and from description that irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the skin of the humans (ACGIH (7th, 2001), DFGOT (vol.6, 1994), PATTY (4th, 1994) and SIDS (2001)), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: pyrazophos
Rationale for classification: In Priority 1, since there was description that irritation is not indicated to skin of rabbits (JMPR852 (1992)), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Iron carbonyl
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (4 hour application) performed in accordance with OECD Test Guideline (IUCLID (2000)): "Not irritating."

Name: Titanium dioxide
Rationale for classification: It was classified as out of Category from the statement of slightly irritating, and not irritating in rabbit examination (IUCLID (2000)).

Name: 2-Naphthol
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from description which does not stimulate a rabbit eye (SIDS, 2006;IUCLID, 2000).

Name: Ethyl acetate
Rationale for classification: As it caused "no irritation" in tests on humans (DFGOT (vol.12, 1999)) and rabbits (IUCLID (2000)), it was classified as "out of Category". Observed effect was "defatting" with long-term repeated skin exposure only.

Name: Emamectin benzoate
Rationale for classification: In the primary skin irritation test using a rabbit, it carried out the outside of Category based on the statement that an irritant effect was not admitted (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: N1-[(6-Chloro-3-pyridyl)methyl]-N2-cyano-N1-methylacetamidine
Rationale for classification: In the primary skin irritation test using a rabbit, it carried out the outside of Category based on the statement that there is no irritation (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Methomyl
Rationale for classification: Since it was judged to have no stimulativeness in the skin irritation test on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 1,1-Dichloro-1-fluoroethane; HCFC-141b
Rationale for classification: Based on the results of rabbit skin irritation tests, SIDS (2003) concludes "it is not irritating to the skin." The substance is thus considered non skin irritant.

Name: Perfluoro(octane-1-sulfonic acid)
Rationale for classification: There is a description, "non-irritating" in the section of Animal Toxity Studies of HSDB (2003). Moreover, there is a description, "Although K salt of this substance stimulated rabbits' eyes but not its skin," in the MOE Risk Assessment Vol 3 (2008). Moreover, when the cited literature from the MOE Risk Assessment Vol 6 (2008) referred for acute toxicity (oral), OECD: Co-operation on Existing Chemicals - Hazard Assessment of Perfluorooctane Sulfonate and its Salts.ENV/JM/RD (2002)17/FINAL.JT00135607, was checked, there was a description, "primary skin irritation scores; 0" in the skin irritation test with 6 rabbits. Because of the above-mentioned reasons it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: N-(Cyclohexan-1-ylsulfanyl)phthalimide
Rationale for classification: Since there are descriptions, "not irritating, PII:1.7/8" (IUCLID (2000)) and "not irritating, PII:1.2/8" (IUCLID (2000)) in the Draize test with rabbits, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: Atrazine
Rationale for classification: Since irritation was not observed in the rabbit skin primary irritation test with 50% hidrated agent was classified as in GLP (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 1989), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Metribuzin
Rationale for classification: Irritation was not observed at all in rabbit skin irritation test (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts). Therefore, it was classified as out of Category. In addition, it is also reported to have no irritativeness on human skin (HSDB, 2005).

Name: O-4-Bromo-2,5-dichlorophenyl O-methyl phenylphosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: In the test of the rabbit of JMPR (WHO Pesticide Residues Series 5, 1975), since it did not indicate skin stimulative to be also drug substances and a tablet, it considered as the outside of Category.

Name: bendiocarb
Rationale for classification: Since there is description that skin irritation is not seen in this product as a result of the animal experiments in Priority 1(PDS 52 (1982)), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: pirimicarb
Rationale for classification: Since irritation was not acknowledged when the this product (5%, 25%, 50% of content) was applied to skin of rabbits (JMPR375 (1976)), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: N',N'-dimethylcarbamoyl(methylthio)methylenamine N-methylcarbamate
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) that irritation was not admitted by the skin irritation test using a guinea pigs, it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: pirimiphos-ethyl
Rationale for classification: From description (HSDB (2003)) that there is no skin irritation to a rabbit, it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 3,5-dichloro-N-(1,1-dimethyl-2-propynyl)benzamide
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of irritant effects with a Draize score of <=1, which were fully reversed within 72 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1994)).

Name: 6-methyl-1,3-dithiolo[4,5-b]quinoxalin-2-one
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: 4,4'-carbonimidoylbis(N,N-dimethylaniline) monohydrochloride
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement of "having no local irritation on rabbit skin" (DFGOT vol.4 (1992)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Di-Butyl phenyl phosphate
Rationale for classification: From description that irritation was not acknowledged by exposure for 24 hours in the test using the rabbit on ACGIH (7th, 2001), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: S-Ethyl 2-(4-chloro-2-methylphenoxy)thioacetate; Phenothiol; MCPA-thioethyl
Rationale for classification: In rabbit skin irritation tests, only mild irritation reactions were seen immediately after the application. The reactions were fully reversible within 48 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1999)).

Name: Dinitrotoluene
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (SIDS (2005)): "non-irritating to the skin; mild erythema."

Name: Ethyl 2-[(dimethoxyphosphinothioyl)thio]-2-phenylacetate; Phenthoate; PAP
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1978)): Non-irritating to the skin.

Name: S-benzyl O,O-diisopropyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: 2-Isopropylphenyl N-methylcarbamate; Isoprocarb; MIPC
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)): "Non-irritating to the skin."

Name: O-4-cyanophenyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 3,5-Dimethylphenyl N-methylcarbamate; XMC
Rationale for classification: Based on the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data): "Non-irritating."

Name: fthalide
Rationale for classification: Since a skin reaction was not admitted in the skin irritation test using a rabbit (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: S-4-chlorobenzyl N,N-diethylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Based on test data from rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2004)): "The treated animals exhibited a Draize score of 0.7, but the effects were fully reversed within 48 hours."

Name: isobenzan
Rationale for classification: From description that skin irritation was not admitted by the examination of the rabbit and the guinea pig (EHC, 129, 1992), and from description that there was no report of humans skin irritation (HSG (Health&Safety Guides), 61, World Health Organization/IPCS, 1991), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: disulfoton
Rationale for classification: In the primary skin irritation test of the rabbit in Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987), very slight stimulativeness (average score: 0.4) was recognized 1 hour after application removal. But impact was not seen in 24 hours after application removal, it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Ethane, 2,2-dichloro-1,1,1-trifluoro-
Rationale for classification: As a result of the skin irritation study on rabbits under the OECD Guidelines, there was no erythema and dropsy, and skin irritation was not found (NICNAS (1999)), therefore, it was classified as out of Category.

Name: isopropyl 3-[[(ethylamino)methoxyphosphinothioyl]oxy]crotonate
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category based on the description that each of erythema / crusta, or average scores of dropsy are less than 1.5 in two examinations in rabbits  (drugs application materials, United States pesticide registration application documents).

Name: 4-chloro-o-toluidinium chloride
Rationale for classification: It was classified as "out of Category" as rat skin did not show irritation after 24 hours of contact (DFGOT vol.6 (1994)).

Name: 3-(3,4-dichlorophenyl)-1-methoxy-1-methylurea
Rationale for classification: In rabbit skin irritation tests, erythematous responses with a Draize score of <=1 were noted 1 hour after application, but the effects cleared up by 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: 3-methyl-1,5-di(2,4-xylyl)-1,3,5-triazapenta-1,4-diene
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Diazinon
Rationale for classification: Since skin changes that matches diagnosis criteria of mild irritation were not observed in the skin irritation test on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 2,3-dicyano-1,4-dithiaanthraquinone
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1975)).

Name: 2-Propanol, 1-(2-methoxypropoxy)- ; Dipropylene Glycol Methyl Ether
Rationale for classification: From description that irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the skin of the rabbit (ACGIH (7th, 2001) and SIDS (2001)), and from description that irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the skin of the humans (ACGIH (7th, 2001), DFGOT (vol.6, 1994), PATTY (4th, 1994) and SIDS (2001)), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: O-2,4-dichlorophenyl O-ethyl S-propyl phosphorodithioate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1975)).

Name: O-ethyl O-(4-methylthiophenyl) S-propyl dithiophosphate
Rationale for classification: It was classified as out of Category from the statement of having no stimulativeness on the examination with rabbits (ACGIH (2001)).

Name: O-Ethyl O-(6-nitro-m-tolyl) sec-butylphosphoramidothioate; Butamifos
Rationale for classification: Based on the data on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1981)): "Non-irritating to the skin."

Name: 2-butylphenyl methylcarbamate
Rationale for classification: Since skin changes that matches criteria of mild irritation were not observed in the skin irritation test on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: ammonium pentadecafluorooctanoate
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that irritation was not observed in rabbit skin irritation test (ACGIH (7th, 2001)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 3,5-diiodo-4-octanoyloxybenzonitrile
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of slight effects with the maximum Draize score of ca. 1.0, which were fully recovered within 4 days, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2001)). The substance is thus considered non-irritating.

Name: Sodium chloroacetate
Rationale for classification: There is a report that skin irritation was not indicated in the rabbit (SIDS (1996)), and it carried out the outside of Category. In addition, the data which is supported was not found although it was considered as those with skin irritation (Xi;R38) in EU-Annex I (Access on June 2005).

Name: 2,2'-{Isopropylidenebis[(2,6-dibromo-4,1-phenylene)oxy]}diethanol
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on primary skin irritation tests (EHC 172 (1995)): mild erythema and edema are observed in 1/3 specimens upon application and after 48 hours of application to unbroken skin; no reaction is observed in broken skin; the score of primary irritation is 0.2, with no primary skin irritation observed. The substance does not cause primary skin irritation, though the results of 4-hour application are not available.

Name: 5-methyl-1,2,4-triazolo[3,4-b]benzo-1,3-thiazole
Rationale for classification: Since change that matches for slight stimulation criteria was not observed with exposure for 24 hours in the skin irritation test on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Diisopropyl 1,3-dithiolan-2-ylidenemalonate; isoprothiolane
Rationale for classification: Since no irritant effect was seen in rabbit skin irritation study (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 2001), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: tetranitromethane
Rationale for classification: Based on description that "the skin is not also stimulated in repeated exposure in humans" of DFGOTvol.4 (1992) or PATTY (4th, 1994) which are the source of Priority 1, it was considered as the outside of Category. In addition, "The skin is stimulated" is described by ICSC (J)(2004), SITTIG (47th, 2002), HSDB (2005) and HSFS (2000) which are sources of Priority 2. It was judged that all were insufficient for considering as basis of the categories since former references were not indicated.

Name: 2-chloro-2'-ethyl-N-(2-methoxy-1-methylethyl)-6'-methylacetanilide
Rationale for classification: In rabbit skin irritation tests, the treated animals exhibited a Draize score of 0.34 at 24 hours, but the effects disappeared by 48 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 2-Amino-4-[hydroxy(methyl)phosphinoyl]butyric acid; Glufosinate
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only slight irritation reactions (a mean Draize score of 0.2), which cleared up by 72 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: alpha-Cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2-(4-chlorophenyl)-3-methylbutyrate; Fenvalerate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of toxic effects observed in human skin irritation studies, along with the absence of irritant effects observed in rabbit skin irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: Dimethyl 2,2,2-trichloro-1-hydroxyethylphosphonate; Trichlorfon; DEP
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of skin irritation reported in more than one skin irritation studies with rabbits (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986, 1987)).

Name: alpha-Cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 3-(2,2-dichlorovinyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylate; Cypermethrin
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of local responses observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 3-phenoxybenzyl 3-(2,2-dichlorovinyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: 2-Thioxo-3,5-dimethyltetrahydro-2H-1,3,5-thiadiazine; Dazomet
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of skin irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: Fenthion
Rationale for classification: Since "there was almost no irritation (Draze score 0.4)"in test on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 1-(4-biphenylyloxy)-3,3-dimethyl-1-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)-2-butanol
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: 2,3-Dihydro-2,2-dimethyl-7-benzo[b]furyl N-(dibutylamino)thio-N-methylcarbamate; Carbosulfan
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only mild irritation (the highest Draize score of 1.2), with effects fully clearing up within 6 days, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1981)).

Name: 2-methyl-N-[3-(1-methylethoxy)phenyl]benzamide
Rationale for classification: Based an irritation response was not observed, and based on being the Draize scores of 0 (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts (1994)), it was classified out of Category

Name: O-3,5,6-trichloro-2-pyridyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: In rabbit skin irritation tests, the treated animals exhibited the highest Draize score of 0.7 and were fully recovered after 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: ethion
Rationale for classification: Since ACGIH (2003) reports that it slightly irritates skin of the rabbit, it was judged not to match the irritation criteria and was classified as out of Category.

Name: Lindane
Rationale for classification: From descriptions that irritation was not observed in the skin irritation test on rabbits (DFGOT (16 vol. 2001) and EHC 124 (1991)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: hexan-2-one
Rationale for classification: PATTY (4th, 1994) and ATSDR (1992) have description with no significant irritation and least severe irritation to the rabbit skin, respectively. Since there was no report which indicates skin irritation with a cases of human exposure, it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 1-Hexene
Rationale for classification: From description that the average Draize scores was 0-1.0 in the skin irritation test using the rabbit (SIDS (2000) and ACGIH (2002)), it was judged that there was no irritation and was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: dimethyl N,N'-[thiobis[(methylimino)carbonyloxy]]bis(thioimidoacetate)
Rationale for classification: In the skin irritation test using a rabbit, it carried out the outside of Category based on the statement that irritation is not admitted (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on Draize skin irritation tests using rabbits (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.14 (2004)): The substance does not cause skin irritation.

Name: O,O-Dimethyl S-(N-methylcarbamoyl)methyl phosphorodithioate; Dimethoate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation reported in several skin irritation studies with rabbits (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: 2,4'-dichloro-alpha-(5-pyrimidinyl)benzhydryl alcohol
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1977)).

Name: 2,6-Dinitrotoluene
Rationale for classification: Based on the results of rabbit skin irritation tests that suggest no skin irritation (CERI Hazard Data 98-15(3) (1998)).

Name: 2,4-Dichloro-1-nitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: Based on descriptions "Slightly irritating" (SIDS (1996)) in the patch test with rabbits and "Slightly irritating" (IUCLID (2000)) in the skin irritation/corrosion test (OECD TG 404, GLP), it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 1-Chloro-2-(chloromethyl)benzene
Rationale for classification: Although it seems to be classified into skin irritation Category 3 in the U.N. GHS from description of "mild skin irritation with less than score 2 in all three rabbits by application for four hours" (SIDS (2004)) in the skin irritation and corrosion test with rabbits (OECD TG 404, GLP), it was classified into "Not classified" because of unemployed category in the country.

Name: Bis(hydrogenated tallow)dimethylammonium chloride
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests performed in accordance with OECD TG404 (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.78 (2005)): 72 hour application of the substance (the test material content: 97%) "showed no evidence of irritation."

Name: sodium fluoroacetate
Rationale for classification: Slight transient edema was observed in one case (HSDB (2005)). But it had concluded that there was no irritation. So it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Isophthalonitrile
Rationale for classification: From description that skin changes were not admitted in the test applied to the skin of the rabbit on ACGIH (7th, 2001), it was judged that there was no irritation and was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 1-methylbutyl acetate
Rationale for classification: There is a report on isomer mixture that skin irritations in short-term exposure is thought to be weak or none (ACGIH (2001), DFGOT vol.11 (1998)). Therefore, it was classified as out of Category. Skin irritation and defatting of the skin were observed in repeated exposure.

Name: S-4-phenoxybutyl N,N-dimethylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: Carbon monoxide
Rationale for classification: It is said to be tasteless odorless gas. (Merck 13th(2001))

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2,2-dichloro-1-(4-ethoxyphenyl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: Ethanol
Rationale for classification: It was classified as out of Category by the statement of "not being stimulative in the test according to OECD TG404 and American guidelines" (DFGOT (1996)).

Name: 1,2-Propanediol, dinitrate
Rationale for classification: From descriptions that irritation was not observed in the rabbit skin irritation test (ACGIH (7th, 2001) and PATTY (4th, 1994)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: N,N'-ethylenebis(thiocarbamoylthiozinc) bis(N,N-dimethyldithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of mild irritation with a Draize score of ca.1.3, which was fully reversed within 7 days, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: Flutolanil
Rationale for classification: As it was judged to have almost no skin irritation in the skin irritation test on guinea pigs (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Methasulfocarb
Rationale for classification: Since irritation was not admitted in primary skin of rabbits irritation test (examination for agricultural-chemicals applications for registration), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 2-Propanol
Rationale for classification: There is a report of no irritation or of mild irritation in the tests for rabbit skin irritation (EHC 103 (1990), PATTY (4th, 1994), ECETOC TR66 (1995), and CERI Hazard Data (1999)). But from the report that irritation was not indicated in the test which was done skin application for the medical treatment of the volunteer and an alcoholism patient in the humans (EHC 103 (1990)), it was set as the outside of Category .

Name: Acetone
Rationale for classification: It was classified as out of Category from the statement of having no stimulativeness on rabbit skin (EHC 207 (1998)) and (SIDS (1999)).

Name: N-propyl-N-[2-(2,4,6-trichlorophenoxy)ethyl]imidazole-1-carboxamide
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)).

Name: N,N-Dimethylformamide
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of "no irritation" from animal eye irritation tests (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.8 (2005)). Accidental exposure to the substance caused skin irritation, according to some report.

Name: Sodium alkyl(C16-18) sulfate
Rationale for classification: This substance has been described as causing "slight irritation" (SIDS (2007)) up to the concentration level of 31,5% in the skin irritation /corrosion test with rabbits (OECD TG 404, GLP). In addition, there is a description, "slightly irritating" (IUCLID (2000)) in the 4 hour sdministration study of this substance alone. It was classified into "Not classified" based on the above-mentioned.

Name: monocrotophos
Rationale for classification: Since ACGIH (2002) describes that no skin irritation was observed in the test on rabbits, it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 2-tert-Butylimino-3-isopropyl-5-phenyltetrahydro-4H-1,3,5-thiadiazin-4-one; buprofezin
Rationale for classification: Since only very slight erythema was found on one out of six rabbits in the skin irritation test (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was classified as out of Category. (in addition, only a guinea pig skin irritation study is indicated in the Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts, and according to this finding, most skin irritation shall be disregarded).

Name: 3',4'-dichloropropionanilide
Rationale for classification: In the available rabbit skin irritation tests, the affected animals exhibited a Draize score of 0.2 at 1 hour after application, but all signs cleared up by 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: 4-[(Hydroxy)(methyl)phosphinyl]-L-Abu-L-Ala-L-Ala-ONa
Rationale for classification: Since block paste of 0.5g of this product did not indicate irritation to the rabbit skin (Pesticide Science Society of Japan, 1987), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 2-[4-(2,4-dichlorobenzoyl)-1,3-dimethyl-5-pyrazolyloxy]acetophenone
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: endrin
Rationale for classification: From descriptions that 24 hour exposure test on rabbits show no skin effects (EHC 130 (1992), DFGOT (vol.18, 2002), and ATSDR (1996)), it was judged that there was no skin irritation and was classified as out of Category.

Name: Methane
Rationale for classification: From the description that the skin is not stimulated in ACGIH (7th, 2001), it carried out the outside of category.

Name: Ethene
Rationale for classification: From the description that the skin is not stimulated in PATTY (4th, 1994), it carried out the outside of category.

Name: Propane
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of category from the description that only slight erythema was acknowledged transiently in the humans of ACIGH (7th, 2001), and the primary skin irritation can be disregarded.

Name: Silver
Rationale for classification: Since it is reported to be "Slightly irritating" on rabbits (IUCLID (2000)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Acetonitrile
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report of rabbit skin irritation tests conducted in line with the EPA/OECD Guidelines (EU-RAR No.18 (2002)): Draize scores are all "0" for all subjects throughout the observation period; no skin irritation is observed.

Name: Ethene, 1,1-difluoro-
Rationale for classification: Since it was gas, skin irritation test was not carried out. But there was no skin irritation as a result of other toxic examinations (SIDS, 2001), it considered as the outside of Category.

Name: Methane, trichlorofluoro-
Rationale for classification: There is the descriptions that although applications on the skin of rats and rabbits indicated transient mild irritation, no damage was observed (CERI Hazard Data (1999), ACGIH (7th, 2001)). And it was judged not to match the diagnostic criteria of irritation and classified as out of Category.

Name: Methane, dichlorodifluoro-
Rationale for classification: Based on the information that it "has a slight irritation" (CERI Hazard Data (1998), EHC 113 (1990)) and "was unirritating" (DFGOT 5th (1993)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Ethane, 1,2-dichlorotetrafluoro-
Rationale for classification: Irritation is not observed on rabbit skin as a result of spray medication with concentration of 40%. (EHC113 (1990), ACGIH (2001)). And also irritation was not observed as a test result of direct spraying on the back of the guinea pigs (EHC113 (1990)), from what stated above, it was classified as out of Category.

Name: heptachlor
Rationale for classification: Based on description that in the rabbit skin application test both original product and 20% phthalates methyl solution show no skin irritation (PATTY (4th, 1994)), it was classified as the outside of Category.

Name: Sodium nitrite
Rationale for classification: There is possibility of skin irritation (HSFS (1999)). But it carried out the outside of category since skin irritation was not seen by the test (compliance with GLP) of the rabbit (IUCLID (1999)).

Name: Ethyl 2-[4-(6-chloro-2-quinoxalinyloxy)phenoxy]propionate; Quizalofop-ethyl
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1982)).

Name: Tris(o-cresyl) phosphate
Rationale for classification: From description that it is not the skin irritation on PATTY (4th, 1994), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 2,2'-Azobisisobutyronitrile
Rationale for classification: Based on the testing data of rabbit skin irritation tests according to OECD Test Guideline 404 (SIDS (2002)), and negative results in human health effects (SIDS (2002)).

Name: Isobutyraldehyde
Rationale for classification: It was classified into "Not classified" since it was thought to be no irritation with PII=0.13 (ECETOC TR66 (1995)) in the skin irritation test with rabbits, and since there were two data of not irritating (IUCLID (2000)) with GLP: yes. In addition, it has been described that "moderate to severe irritation and burn in rabbits and erythema in one of six rabbits" (SIDS (2004)), "including irritation on the skin" (NTP TR472 (1999)), and "similar irritaion to other aldehydes" (Patty (5th, 2001)) were determined in the skin irritation test with rabbits. However, any data was shown in 1952 with unknown GLP and test conditions.

Name: Butan-2-ol
Rationale for classification: Since it was described that there was no skin irritation in the test using the rabbit, and there was no report that indicated skin irritation in the example of human exposure (EHC 65 (1987), ACGIH (2002), DFGOT vol.19 (2003), and PATTY (4th, 1994)), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Methyl acetate
Rationale for classification: Based on the descriptions that it has no stimulation with application on humans (EU-RAR (2003),(DFGOTvol.18 (2002)) and that it has no stimulation on rabbits (EU-RAR (2003)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Ethane, nitro-
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of Category from description that irritation was not admitted in the skin irritation test using the rabbit on HSDB (2005), and description that the irritation to the rabbit skin was weak on DFGOT (vol.19, 2003) .

Name: Propane, 2-nitro-
Rationale for classification: From description that when applied to the skin of the rabbit on EHC 138 (1992), local effects were not admitted, it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: N-(1,3-Dimethylbutyl)-N'-phenyl-1,4-phenylenediamine
Rationale for classification: Based on the description, " The average score of the 6 animals is less stimulative than 0.0/8.0,"(SIDS (2004)) in the 4-hour study with rabbits, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 2,3,5,6-Tetrafluoro-4-methylbenzyl (Z)-3-(2-chloro-3,3,3-trifluoro-1-propenyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylate; Tefluthrin
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only mild irritation (a mean Draize score of <=0.5), with effects resolving within 48 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1992)).

Name: 3-chloro-N-(3-chloro-5-trifluoromethyl-2-pyridyl)-alpha,alpha,alpha-trifluoro-2,6-dinitro-p-toluidine
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of very mild irritation with a Draize score of 0.25, which were reversed within 72 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: 2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-1-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)-2-hexanol
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: 4,4'-Isopropylidenediphenol; Bisphenol A
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit primary skin irritation tests (4 hour dermal application) (EU-RAR No.37 (2003): Bisphenol A does not cause skin irritation, given the absence of skin reactions such as erythema and edema.

Name: 2-Phenyl-2-[(2-phenylpropan-2-yl)peroxy]propane
Rationale for classification: For patch tests in human, there have been descriptions of "slight" irritation (DFGOT vol.3 (1992)) and "slight" irritation in the patch test to 200 volunteers (Patty (5th, 2001)). Moreover, for rats, although there has been a description of "mild" irritation (Patty (5th, 2001)), and it seems to be equivalent to skin irritation Category 3 in the U.N. GHS, it was classified into "Not classified" with unemployed catergory in the country. It can be classified as Xi in the EU classification; R36/ 38 (EU-Annex I).

Name: Benzenesulfonic acid, 4,4'-oxybis-, dihydrazide
Rationale for classification: Based on the report of having no skin stimulativeness on rabbits (ACGIH (2001)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Paraffin wax
Rationale for classification: It is estimated to be mild (RTECS (2003)) and "not irritating" (IUCLID (2000)) in rabbit tests. But it was classified as out of Category because it is estimated as "not irritating" in the human skin application test (IUCLID (2000)).

Name: 1-tert-Butyl-3-(2,6-diisopropyl-4-phenoxyphenyl)thiourea; Diafenthiuron
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only slight irritation reactions (a Draize score of <=1), which cleared up within 48 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: Complex compounds of manganese N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate) and zinc N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: Based on test data from rabbit skin corrosivity studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987)): "Erythematous responses were noted immediately after the application, but the affected animals exhibited scores of 0 at 72 hours."

Name: 2-(4-ethoxyphenyl)-2-methylpropyl 3-phenoxybenzyl ether
Rationale for classification: Based on description that it was judged to have no irritation as a result of skin primary irritation examination on rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts (1986)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: diphacinone
Rationale for classification: Since there was description that there was no skin irritation in Priority 1 (PM (13th, 2003)), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Pentachloronitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: Based on the descriptions that there was no irritation observed in the rabbit skin irritation test (JMPR and (1996), CERI Hazard Data (2002)) and that there was no primary irritation in the PCNB 75% hidrated agent skin application test on 50 persons (ACGIH and (7th 2001), JMPR (1969)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Stearic acid, sodium salt
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement that there is no irritation with the rabbit (ACGIH (2001)), it was carried out the outside of Category .

Name: ethyl N-[2,3-dihydro-2,2-dimethylbenzofuran-7-yloxycarbonyl(methyl)aminothio]-N-isopropyl-beta-alaninate
Rationale for classification: In the skin irritation test of rabbits, it carried out the outside of Category based on the statement that skin irritation is not admitted (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: 2-Methyl-1,1'-biphenyl-3-ylmethyl (Z)-3-(2-chloro-3,3,3-trifluoro-1-propenyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylate; Bifenthrin
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests, reported in Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1991).

Name: 1-(3,5-dichloro-2,4-difluorophenyl)-3-(2,6-difluorobenzoyl)urea
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)).

Name: alanycarb
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of category based on the primary skin irritation test using a rabbit, in which the irritation was admitted in neither of the animals, and the primary irritation index (P. I.I.) has also been 0 (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) .

Name: Aniline, 4,4'-methylenebis(2-methyl)-
Rationale for classification: It was classified as "out of Category" as it does not indicate irritation in rabbit test (IUCLID (2000)).

Name: Dicyclohexan-1-yl phthalate
Rationale for classification: Since there are descriptions, "not irritating" in the skin irritation/corrosion test with rabbits (OECD TG 404) and "slightly irritating" in the study with guinea pig (CERI/NITE Hazard Assessment Report (2008)), it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: Diisobutyl phthalate
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests performed in accordance with OECD Test Guideline 404 (IUCLID (2000)): "Not irritating."

Name: Di-n-butyl phthalate
Rationale for classification: Addendum of European Union-RAR (2004) were absent from the investigation subject of substance data. Although a description of skin irritation has been shown in CERI/NITE Hazard Assessment Report No.11 (2004) and EU-RAR No.29 (2003), it was modified to "Not classified" because of descriptions of the result of no irritation in the test based on OECD TG404 and no irritation as a conclusion in the addendum European Union-RAR (2004) (addendum to the Environmental section) of EU-RAR No.29 (2003).

Name: Alkanes, C10-13, chloro(shortchain chlorinated paraffins)
Rationale for classification: There is an information that erythema and slight edema could be seen in rabbits but such symptoms disappeared (carbon number C10-13/chloridization rate 70%) within 7 days (EU-RAR (1999)). In this datum the score value for erythema of 2 out of 3 animals is 1 (maximum: 4) and the score value for edema of 2 out of 3 animals is 1 (maximum:4 until 24 hours after application). There is an information about humans beside them that although slight erythema and dry skin were observed, the effect (carbon number C10-12/ chloridization rate 5-% 63%) was corresponding to that of the control group or there was no symptom (carbon number C12/chloridization rate 59%), and there is an information about rabbits that there is no irritation (carbon number C10-13/chloridization rate 59%) (EU-RAR (1999)). It was classified into "Not classified" based on the above-mentioned.

Name: O,O-dimethyl-4-oxobenzotriazin-3-ylmethyl phosphorodithioate
Rationale for classification: Since irritation is not caused in rabbit test(ACGIH (2002), JMPR 818 (1991)), it classified as out of Category.

Name: 4-chlorobenzyl N-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)thioacetimidate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: 1-vinyl-2-pyrrolidone
Rationale for classification: Since it has been concluded not to be "skin irritation" based on the recent studies (HRC (1978) and BASF (1996) that observed almost no irritation with rats and guinea pig, it was classified into "Not classified", although severe skin irritation was observed in the previous tests with rabbit (BASF (1941,1953)) in EU-RAR (2003) and NICNAS (2000).

Name: 2-Nitrotoluene
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of Category from description that irritation was not indicated in the skin of the rabbit on CERI Hazard Data (1999) and DFGOT (vol.8, 1997).

Name: Benzene, 1-chloro-2-nitro-
Rationale for classification: One test indicated minor irritations in rabbit experiments. But it carried out the outside of category since effect was not acknowledged by two another examinations and they concluded "it had no proof of skin irritation (SIDS (2001))".

Name: O-3-tert-butylphenyl N-(6-methoxy-2-pyridyl)-N-methylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: pyraclofos
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category based on the statement that an irritant effect was not admitted in the skin irritation test using rabbits (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: fentin acetate
Rationale for classification: Since irritation was not indicated to skin of rabbits (CICAD 13, 1999;JMPR 827, 1991), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Poly(oxyethylene) octylphenyl ether
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on epidemiological studies of human exposure (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.105 (2006)): "OPE with average EO chain lengths of 1, 3, 5, 8-10, 12-13 (i.e., OPE1, OPE3, OPE5, OPE8-10, OPE12-13) caused no primary skin irritation," "OPE with EO chain lengths of 3 and longer showed no primary skin irritation." The materials are thus considered non skin irritants.

Name: Phthalonitrile
Rationale for classification: Slight irritation was reported for the 24-hour test on guinea pigs. But based on the results that irritation was not observed in four rabbit examinations (SIDS (2001), IUCLID (2000)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Benzene, 1-methoxy-2-nitro-
Rationale for classification: Since the skin irritation was not observed in rabbit examination (DFGOT vol.9 (1998)), it was classified as "out of Category."

Name: Sodium cyanate
Rationale for classification: In the primary skin irritation test in rabbits of the agricultural newsletter supplement No. (1994) 17, it disappeared in 24 hours although slight erythema was seen in all patients 1 hour afterward as a result of exposing 1.0g (0.5g as this product) of samples for 4 hours, it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: fonofos
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement that skin irritation was not indicated on rabbits (ACGIH (2001), PATTY (5th, 2001)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: N-(tert-Butyl)-2-benzothiazolesulfenamide
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests evaluated according to the Draize scheme (SIDS (2004)): "It can be concluded that the substance is essentially non irritating to the human skin, though only slight irritation was observed." Also based on the description in CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.22 (2005): "There is no evidence of skin irritation."

Name: N-Cyclohexyl-2-benzothiazolesulfenamide
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on the rabbit skin irritation tests (CERI Hazard Data 2001-25 (2002)): "24-hour application did not produce any signs of irritation of the skin."

Name: o-Chloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (4 hours) performed in accordance with OECD Test Guideline 404 (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.58 (2004)): "non-irritating to the skin."

Name: 2,4-Dimethylaniline
Rationale for classification: It is described as "not irritating" (DFGOT Vol. 19 (1998)).for the skin irritation test comforming to OECD TG. Moreover, it is described as "skin: weak irritation" in BUA 161 (Summary, 1994). Although it seemed to correspond to UN GHS Skin irritation Category 3 based on the above-mentioned, it was classified into "Not classified", because Category 3 is not domestically adopted. In addition, there is a description, "It stimulates the skin.........causes reddening, when contacting the skin" in the section of Effects on Humans of the MOE Risk Assessment Vol 6 (2008). Moreover, there is a description "mildly irritating" in the section of EFFECTS OF SHORT-TERM EXPOSURE in the cited literature ICSC (2007).

Name: 3,4-Dichloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Since there are descriptions, "slightly irritating, erythema grade 1, recovery within 2 days" (EU-RAR (2006), IUCLID (2000)) in the Draize test using rabbits (OECD TG404, GLP) and "not irritating" (IUCLID (2000)) in the 24 hour skin irritation test using rabbits, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: S-(2,3-Dihydro-5-methoxy-2-oxo-1,3,4-thiadiazol-3-yl)methyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorodithioate; Methidathion; DMTP
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only mild irritation (mean Draize score of 1.2), with effects fully clearing after 72 hours, observed in rabbit skin irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987)), that suggests little potential for skin irritation.

Name: cadusafos
Rationale for classification: In the primary skin irritation examination of the rabbit, based on the statement that irritation is not admitted (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Dibromochloropropane
Rationale for classification: When it was applied to the normal skin in rabbit test, there was no irritation, and since even when it was applied to the brushing skin, only very slight erythema was observed. Therefore, it was classified as out of Category.

Name: Propane, 1,2,3-trichloro-
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of Category from description that the skin of the rabbit was not stimulated on ACGIH (7th, 2001), and description that irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the rabbit skin for 4 hours on CICAD 56 (2003).

Name: 2-tert-Butyl-5-(4-tert-butylbenzylthio)-4-chloro-3(2H)-pyridazinone; Pyridaben
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)): Non-irritating to the skin.

Name: Disulfiram
Rationale for classification: In the test applied to the skin of the rabbit of DFGOT (vol.5, 1993), slight erythema was admitted, but it disappeared 6 hours afterward. Acceptance criteria of irritation was not suited and it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: fosthiazate
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) by very slight erythema only having been seen in the rabbit, it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 1,3,5-trinitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: From description that irritation was not admitted by the skin irritation test using the rabbit of IRIS (1997), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: 1,2-Dichloro-4-nitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: Since the 24 hour skin irritation/corrosion test with rabbits (OECD TG 404, GLP) did not identify skin irritation (average scored values for erythema/crust and edema:0.2, 0.0) (SIDS (2003)), it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: Methyl 4-hydroxybenzoate
Rationale for classification: For human, while there is a description of "non-irritating in normal human skin", it has been described that "the highest concentration of this substance was 5% when dissolved solution was applied to 50 persons' back every day during five days and irritation was not indicated" (HSDB (2007)). For animals, it has been described that "it was estimated as mild skin irritation from PII= 0.67 (up to 4.0) with non-dissolved solution" (HSDB (2007)) in a 24-hour Draize test with rabbits. As mentioned above, although this substance seems to be equivalent to skin irritation Category 3 in the U.N. GHS, it was classified into "Not classified" with unemployed category in the country.

Name: 4-Nitrotoluene
Rationale for classification: In the test applied to the skin of the rabbit on SIDS (2005), from description that irritation was not acknowledged by zero of Draize score, it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Methyl 3-chloro-5-(4,6-dimethoxy-2-pyrimidinylcarbamoylsulfamoyl)-1-methylpyrazole-4-carboxylate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, the treated animals exhibited a mean Draize score of 0.7, and were fully recovered (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: 4,4'-oxybisbenzenamine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was carried out the outside of Category from the statement of having no stimulativeness (DFGOTvol.6 (1994)) by the examination of the rabbit.

Name: 2,4-bis(ethylamino)-6-methylthio-1,3,5-triazine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: 1-[(6-Chloro-3-pyridyl)methyl]imidazolidine-2-(N-nitro)imine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Due to the description that ocular symptoms was not observed in each animal in rabbits test (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was set as the out of Category.

Name: Methyl isobutyl ketone
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Although we found the descriptions that irritant property was seen in human vapor exposure examples (CERI Hazard Data (2000), EHC 117 (1990), ACGIH (7th, 2001), and PATTY (4th 1994)), we found no case reports about the case where liquid droplets entered into the eyes. On the other hand, by the Draize tests using the rabbits in ECETOC TR 48 (1992), change of the eye which suited the criteria for diagnosis of irritation was not acknowledged, and the change recovered within seven days, in addition, in the 24-instituites-joint multicenter comparison trial by the unification standard examining method using the rabbit in PATTY (4th 1994), it was estimated that it had no irritant property in 75% (18 institutes). Therefore we classified it as out of Category.

Name: Diisobutyl ketone
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Each of three test results reported is slight stimuli, and is not classified into eye irritation (SIDS (1998), DFGOT vol.18 (2002)).

Name: 1,3,5-trioxan
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: GESTIS (2003) describes as "When the various tests employing "rabbits were summarized, it was slightly stimulative" and since this expression corresponds to "Not classified", it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 2-(2-methoxyethoxy)ethanol
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since it has been described that, in OECD guideline studies employing rabbits, there was no irritation (EU-RAR (2000)), it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 2-(4-Bromodifluoromethoxyphenyl)-2-methylpropyl 3-phenoxybenzyl ether; Hhalfenprox
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)): "Only mild irritation was seen immediately after the application with a Draize score of 0.2 at 24 hours, and the reactions cleared up by 48 hours." The substance is thus considered non-irritating to the skin.

Name: thiacloprid
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Due to the description that it has no irritation in the eye irritation tests using rabbit (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was set as the outsaide of Category.

Name: N-tert-butyl-N'-(4-ethylbenzoyl)-3,5-dimethylbenzohydrazide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: Endosulfan
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From the result (JMPR (1998)) of "not irritayting to eyes" by the eye irritation test using a rabbit, it was classified out of Category.

Name: Benzene, hexachloro-
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: We classified it as out of Category based on the descriptions that it had no ocular irritant property in the laboratory animals although the species of the animals tested was unknown(EHC 195 (1997), DFGOT (vol.16, 2001)).

Name: O,O-diethyl O-(1,6-dihydro-6-oxo-1-phenylpyridazin-3-yl) thiophosphate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since eye irritation was not admitted in the eye irritation test using a rabbit (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 1,2,4-Trichlorobenzene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: For animals, since EU-RAR (2003) has descriptions of "In OECD TG405 conformity test, affection on the cornea and the iris is not seen, and the redness score is 1, the edema score is 0-2" in the conjunctival" and "It was shown that there was no irritation to eyes when EU standard was followed." , it was classified into "Not classified". In addition, although EU-RAR (2003) also has a description of "obvious pain, critical conjunctivitis, and conjunctiva dropsy are seen in irritating to the eyes of rabbits" in the test employing rabbits according to a method given in "US Federal Register, for this test, it has been described that "The interpretation of Draize score differs in US and EU and it will become severer evaluation than usual if the criterion of US is used." and it has been concluded that "Although this substance seems to have a certain eye irritation, it is thought that the effect is not a degree which meets the criterion of Xi; R36." For humans, although MOE Risk Assessment, Volume 4 (2005)) has a description of "An eye is irritated and the eye redness and pain manifest as acute symptoms." as impact to humans, this description has quoted ICSC which is the information source of List3.

Name: 5-Amino-1-[2,6-dichloro-4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-3-cyano-4-[(trifluoromethyl)sulfinyl]pyrazole; Fipronil
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, mild conjunctival redness was noted with a mean Draize score of 0.44. The reactions resolved by Day 3 (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)). The substance is thus considered non-irritating.

Name: 2,4-Dinitrotoluene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit skin irritation tests (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.51 (2004)): "mild irritation" (though exposure time is unknown).

Name: Malathon
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change applicable to the stimulative judging standard indicated in the technical indicator by the test using a rabbit was not admitted (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: methyl cyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the test applied to the eyes of the rabbits, the change of the eyes applicable to 1-3 of the stimulative judging standard was not acknowledged (NICNAS (2003)). Therefore we classified it as Out Of Category.

Name: Zinc N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate); Zineb
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the data from rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)): "Non-irritating to the eye."

Name: Fenitrothion
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change which suited to acceptance criteria of irritation by the test using a rabbit was not admitted (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: butyl (R)-2-[4-(4-cyano-2-fluorophenoxy)phenoxy]propionate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, mild irritation was noted immediately after instillation with a score of 0.2, but the effects cleared up by 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: N,N-diethyl-3-(2,4,6-trimethylphenylsulfonyl)-1H-1,2,4-triazole-1-carboxamide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of conjunctival effects with a mean score of <=1.0, which disappeared by 48 hours, observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1955)).

Name: tris(2,3-dibromopropyl) phosphate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the descriptions that it showed no irritant property in the eye irritation tests applied to the eyes of the rabbits (EHC 173 1995; IARC 20, 1979-ATTY 4th, 1994), we classified it as Out Of Category.

Name: Diantimony trioxide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the three-ministry GHS classification, it is classified as "Category 2B " based on the test result of "Mild irritation to eyes of rabbits at 100mg dose" indicated in RTECS. On the other hand, in the public comment literature (LPT (2005)), it is clearly specified as "non-irritating" from the test result employing a rabbit of the GLP test organization according to the OECD test guidelines. That is, there exists each one case of positive and negative in the test employing a rabbit. According to the public comments, the literature of LPT (2005) is not open to the public. But it was available through common routes and was used for our reference. The former study with the positive result was performed in 1972, and the details in description of the substance used and the symptoms are unknown. On the other hand, the latter study with the negative result was performed in conformity with the the OECD Test Guideline, 2002, and the details in the origin and description of the substance and symptoms generated are described. Therefore, it may be considered that the latter study with the negative result is more reliable than the former one. Therefore, it is considered proper that classification of the substance should be corrected from "Category 2B" to "Not classified".

Name: Zinc oxide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the report of three affairs currently recorded and selected by EU-RAR (2004), two affairs had a very slight stimulus and one affair did not stimulate. And EU-RAR (2004) had judged no stimulating. So it was set as "Outsaide of Category ."

Name: Iron carbonyl
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit eye irritation tests performed in accordance with OECD Test Guideline 405 (IUCLID (2000)): "Not irritating."

Name: O,O-Diethyl O-2-quinoxalinyl phosphorothioate; Quinalphos
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)): "Non-irritating to the eye."

Name: ethoxydimethylsilane
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that in the eye irritation tests (standards Draize's method) using the rabbits, irritation was not indicated (ACGIH 7th, 2001), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 2-chloro-2',6'-diethyl-N-(methoxymethyl)acetanilide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on test data from rabbit eye irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1998)): "Non-irritating to the eye."

Name: N1-[(6-Chloro-3-pyridyl)methyl]-N2-cyano-N1-methylacetamidine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Due to the description that it has no irritation in the eye irritation tests using rabbit (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was set as the out of Category.

Name: Methomyl
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eye which was adapted to criteria for assessments of irritation in eye irritation tests using rabbits was not admitted (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: N-[2-[1-(4-Chlorophenyl)-1H-pyrazole-3-yloxymethyl]phenyl]-N-methoxycarbamic acid methyl ester
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the eye irritation tests using a rabbit, each average marks of the cornea and the iris in application 24 to 72 hours were 0.0, and ophthalmic grade are 1.7 in redness and 0.6 in the dropsy. And it wes completely reversible in eight days (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data). So it was set as the outside of Category according to the technical indicator.

Name: Metribuzin
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on that irritation against ocular-mucous and response to corneal were not produced in eye irritation tests with rabbits (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: N',N'-dimethylcarbamoyl(methylthio)methylenamine N-methylcarbamate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that it has no irritation by the eye irritation tests using rabbit (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it is out of the Category .

Name: 3,5-dichloro-N-(1,1-dimethyl-2-propynyl)benzamide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of conjunctival effects with a Draize score of <=1, which cleared up within 4 days, observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1994)).

Name: Di-Butyl phenyl phosphate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that it did not show irritant property in the test applied to the eyes of the rabbits (ACGIH (7th, 2001)), we classified it as Out Of Category .

Name: Dinitrotoluene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: SIDS (2005) reports that in a rabbit eye irritation test "one animal exhibited mild erythema which persisted for 24 hours." However, the study concludes that the substance is "non-irritating."

Name: Ethyl 2-[(dimethoxyphosphinothioyl)thio]-2-phenylacetate; Phenthoate; PAP
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1975)): Non-irritating to the eye.

Name: O-4-cyanophenyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 3,5-Dimethylphenyl N-methylcarbamate; XMC
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of only slight irritation reactions (a mean Draize score of <=1), with effects resolving by Day 7, observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2004)).

Name: fthalide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the eye irritation tests using a rabbit, the change in the eyes that is applicable to the acceptance criteria of irritation was not acknowledged (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts). So it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: S-4-chlorobenzyl N,N-diethylthiocarbamate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, the only finding was conjunctival redness with a Draize score of 1 at 1 hour after application. The effects cleared up by 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2004)).

Name: Chlorpyrifos
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eye which is adapted for basis of irritation was not admitted in the test applied to the eye of the rabbit (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: disulfoton
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the primary eye irritation examination with the rabbit in Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987), although very slight stimulativeness (the average score in a conjunctival: redness 0.6-1, edema 0.7-0.8) was accepted in after-apply 1 hour, the effect was not seen in after-apply 24 hours. So it was carried out the outside of Category.

Name: isopropyl 3-[[(ethylamino)methoxyphosphinothioyl]oxy]crotonate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: There is the descriptions in two examinations in the rabbit that acne cornea or opacity are not observed, iris is normal, no affluxion and edema are observed in conjunctiva (the documents of approval of new drug applications, the documents of United States registration application of insecticide). So it was not classified.

Name: N,N-Dimethyl-1,2,3-trithian-5-amine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the rabbit, it set as the outside of Category based on the statement (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) that eye irritation was not seen.

Name: 3-(3,4-dichlorophenyl)-1-methoxy-1-methylurea
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, conjunctival redness with a Draize score of <=1 was noted 24 hours after instillation, but the effects disappeared by 48 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: 3-methyl-1,5-di(2,4-xylyl)-1,3,5-triazapenta-1,4-diene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, the treated animals exhibited a mean Draize score of 0.8 at 24 hours, and were fully recovered within 7 days (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Diazinon
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eye which is adapted for criteria for diagnosis of irritation was not admitted in the eye irritation test using a rabbit (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: O-ethyl O-(4-methylthiophenyl) S-propyl dithiophosphate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was set as the outside of Category from the statement of having no stimulativeness (ACGIH (2001)) by the examination of the rabbit.

Name: O-Ethyl O-(6-nitro-m-tolyl) sec-butylphosphoramidothioate; Butamifos
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the data on rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1981)): "Non-irritating to the eye."

Name: 2-butylphenyl methylcarbamate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eye which is adapted for criteria for diagnosis of irritation was not admitted as a result of the eye stimulativeness examination using a rabbit (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 3,5-diiodo-4-octanoyloxybenzonitrile
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of slight effects with the maximum Draize score of ca. 1.0, which resolved within 24 hours, observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)). The substance is thus considered non-irritating.

Name: 2,2'-{Isopropylidenebis[(2,6-dibromo-4,1-phenylene)oxy]}diethanol
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on eye irritation tests (EHC 172 (1995)): "the substance causes no eye irritation."

Name: 5-methyl-1,2,4-triazolo[3,4-b]benzo-1,3-thiazole
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eye which was adapted to criteria for assessments of irritation in eye irritation tests of rabbits was not admitted (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: N,N-Dicyclohexan-1-yl(1,3-benzothiazol-2-ylsulfanyl)amine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: SIDS (2004) has described as "Not irritating" in the eye irritation test employing rabbits and as "slightly" in Draize test. As a conclusion, since SIDS (2004) has described as "slightly irritating to eyes in rabbits", it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 3-(3,5-Dichlorophenyl)-5-methyl-5-vinyl-1,3-oxazolidine-2,4-dione
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From a description of "not irritating to the eyes" in the eye irritation test employing rabbits (JMPR (1995)), it was classified into "Not classified ".

Name: 2-chloro-2'-ethyl-N-(2-methoxy-1-methylethyl)-6'-methylacetanilide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 2-Amino-4-[hydroxy(methyl)phosphinoyl]butyric acid; Glufosinate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In rabbit eye irritation tests, the affected animals exhibited the highest Draize score of 1 (conjunctival redness noted at 24 hours); the reactions resolved within 48 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: alpha-Cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2-(4-chlorophenyl)-3-methylbutyrate; Fenvalerate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritant effects observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: 3-phenoxybenzyl 3-(2,2-dichlorovinyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: 2-Thioxo-3,5-dimethyltetrahydro-2H-1,3,5-thiadiazine; Dazomet
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of very mild irritation (the highest mean Draize score of 0.6 by 72 hours), with effects fully resolving by 72 hours, observed in rabbit eye irritation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: Fenthion
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified out of Category based on the result of "no stimulativeness"in rabbit test (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts).

Name: 1-(4-biphenylyloxy)-3,3-dimethyl-1-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)-2-butanol
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the evidence of mild irritation with a Draize score of <=1, which cleared at 72 hours, observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: O-6-Chloro-3-phenyl-4-pyridazinyl S-n-octyl thiocarbonate; Pyridate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description in the report on rabbit eye irritation tests (IUCLD (2000)): "Not irritating."

Name: 2-methyl-N-[3-(1-methylethoxy)phenyl]benzamide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: The irritant property was not acknowledged, and it scores 0 in Draize scores (Agrichemical-Chemicals Abstracts (1994)). So we classified it as Out Of Category.

Name: O-3,5,6-trichloro-2-pyridyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the available rabbit eye irritation tests, mild effects were noted immediately after instillation, but the effects cleared up by 24 hours (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: ethion
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From description that the eye of the rabbit was stimulated only slightly (only slightly) on ACGIH (2003), it was judged that it was not adapted for basis of irritation, and was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 4-(2,4-dichlorobenzoyl)-1,3-dimethyl-5-pyrazolyl 4-toluenesulfonate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1978)).

Name: 1-Hexene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since change of the eyes which corresponded to the standard of irritant property was not acknowledged in the ocular irritation tests using the rabbits (SIDS (2000) and ACGIH (2002)), we classified it as Out Of Category.

Name: triphenylamine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: There is the description that in the test applied to the eye of the rabbit, damage was not acknowledged (ACGIH (7th, 2001)). As judging that there was no eye irritations, it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 2,6-Dinitrotoluene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the results of rabbit eye irritation tests that suggest no eye irritation (CERI Hazard Data 98-15(3) (1998)).

Name: 2,4-Dichloro-1-nitrobenzene
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From the description of "Slightly irritating" (SIDS (1996)) and "Slightly irritating" in eye irritation/corrosion test (OECD TG 405, GLP) (IUCLID (2000)) in a rabbit, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 4-methoxy-m-phenylenediamine
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: By the examination with a rabbit, since there was a non-stimulated result, it was carried out "Category Outside."

Name: Hydrogenated terphenyl
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From the description of "nonirritating" (ACGIH (7th, 2001)) and of "Draize score:0.3/110" in the eye irritation/corrosion test employing rabbits (OECD TG 405, GLP) (IUCLID (2000)) to eyes of rabbits, it was classified into "Not classified ".

Name: Isophthalonitrile
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that no irritant property was acknowledged in the test applied to the eyes of the rabbits (ACGIH (7th, 2001)), we classified it as Out Of Category.

Name: S-4-phenoxybutyl N,N-dimethylthiocarbamate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: Carbon monoxide
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It is called tasteless odorless gas. (Merck 13th.(2001))

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2,2-dichloro-1-(4-ethoxyphenyl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on no evidence of irritation observed in rabbit eye irritation tests (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 1,2-Propanediol, dinitrate
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From description that change of the eye disappeared within 24 hours by the test applied to the eye of the rabbit (ACGIH (7th, 2001), PATTY (4th, 1994)), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: Flutolanil
Classification: Serious eye damage / eye irritation - Not classified
