Rationale for classification: It was carried out of the Category because significant toxicity is not ackowledged by over dose of the guidance value range of Category 2 in an administration test in drinking water for 90 days using the rat of ACGIH (7th, 2001) and IARC 63 (1995)

Name: Ethane, 1,2-dichlorotetrafluoro-
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since symptom had appeared in rat inhalation administration in a high amount dose of 1422 g/m3 (200000 ppm), it considered as the outside of Category.

Name: Ethane, chloropentafluoro-
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the case of human occupational exposure (PATTY (5th, 2001)) and the toxicity studies of an animal (PATTY and (5th, 2001), (EHC 113 (1990) and (ACGIH (2001)), since effects on organ had come out of neither of the results, it was carried out the out of Category.

Name: Ammonium sulphamate
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since in the rats oral administrations test, toxic effects was not admitted over 250 mg/kg/day or the upper limit of the guidance value range of Cagegory 2 (10-100 mg/kg/day) (ACGIH (7th, 2001), HSDB (2005)), it was classified to as the outside of Category.

Name: Disodium peroxydisulfate
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: From description that toxicity was not observed with the dose which exceeds the guidance value range for Category 2 in 90 day feeding oral administration test on rats (NICNAS (2001) and ACGIH (7th, 2001)), it was classified as out of Category.

Name: 1-Propanol, 2-methyl-
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: We categorized it to be Out Of Category because the toxicity which endorses the classification was not observed with the dose  which exceeds the guidance value of Category 2, and we had no clear toxic report in the human exposure cases in the 90-day inhalation exposure test (exposure concentrations: 0, 250, 1000 or 2500 ppm)(SIDS (2004), DFGOT vol.29 (2003)), in the 90-day forcible oral administration test (dose: 0, 100, 316 or 1000mg/kg/day) using the rat  (SIDS (2004), IRIS (Access on Aug 2005) ) and in the administration test in drinking water for 90 days using the rat (presumed dose: 0, 80, 340 or 1450mg/kg/day) (SIDS (2004), DFGOT vol.19 (2003) and PATTY (4th, 1994)).

Name: phosphine
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that the serious toxic effect by the highest dosage within a repeatedable doses was not acknowledged and no acknowledgement of death in the inhalation exposure test using a rat, a mouse or a guinea pig of EHC 73 (1988), IRIS (2006) and industrial hygiene academic society advice (1998), and the discription that in ocupational evidence of exposure,  symptom was acknowledged for every exposure, but there is no a chronic effects in ACGIH (7th, 2001) and industrial hygiene academic society advice (1998), so it was classified to as the outside of Category.

Name: Propionic acid
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: We classified it as Out Of Category because minimum toxicity expression levels in the repeated oral administration test for 110 days and for two years in the rat, and the repeated oral administration test for 90 days in the dog exceeded over the guidance value range of Category 2 by 10 or more times (RTECS (2005)). In addition, it is recognized that it does not affect human, or it is safe even if human ingests it, and it has description that it is used as an antiseptic etc (PATTY (4th, 1994)).

Name: Paraffin wax
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In the study which carried out feeding administration by the dosage beyond the guidance value of Category 2(5000mg/kg bw) to the rat during two years, toxic effects was not acknowledged (EHC20 (1982)).  Based on this statement, it was considerd as outside of Category.

Name: 2-(4-ethoxyphenyl)-2-methylpropyl 3-phenoxybenzyl ether
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It is considered outside of Category according to that in the 13-week oral study using rats and micewith the dose exceeding the maximum of the guidance value range, serious toxic effect is not acknowledged (Agricultural Chemicals abstracts (1986)) and (JMPR 863 (1993)) .

Name: Diethylphthalate
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was considered to be the Out Of Category based on the descriptions that toxic effects were not observed for the high doses which exceeds the guidance value range of Category 2 in oral or the dermal administration tests using the rat or mouse (MOE Risk Assessment 3rd volume (2004), CICAD 52 (2003), ACGIH (7th, 2001), NTP TR429 (1995), ATSDR (1995), and IRIS (2005)).

Name: Alkanes, C10-13, chloro(shortchain chlorinated paraffins)
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: According to EU-RAR (1999), in a 90-day oral administration study in rats, weight increases in the liver and kidney and mild nephritis (carbon number C10-12/chlorination ratio 58%) in males were observed at 100 mg/kg. However, it was reported in EU-RAR (1999) that "the increase in liver weight reflects peroxisome proliferation, to which humans are not highly susceptible, so this is not relevant for human health," "it is uncertain if the effects on the kidney are toxicologically significant," and "the dosage at which other effects manifest themselves in rats is greater than 100 mg/kg." Using the reports in EU-RAR (1999), which are based on expert opinion, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: 4-(1,3-benzothiazol-2-yldisulfanyl)morpholine
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It is written in 28-day repeated oral administration test in rats (OECD TG407, GLP) that" there were no changes resulting from administration in behavioral function (FOB), sensory response, grip strength, motor activity, urine test, hematologic test, biochemical exam of blood, autopsy, and histological examination by administration of up to 1,000 mg/kg (90-day equivalent: 311 mg/kg) (Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare reports (Access on October 2008)). As mentioned above, it was classified into "Not classified ".

Name: 4-chloro-o-phenylenediamine
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on the statement that damage to organ was not seen in rats and mice in oral administration study with dosage far higher than the upper limit of the guidance value range of Category 2, (IARC and (1982), PATTY (5th, 2001)), it was classified to as outside of Category.

Name: n-Butyl methacrylate
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: In an oral administration study in rats by Ito et al. (1998), red pulp atrophy was observed. This red pulp atrophy is caused by a reduction in extramedullary hematopoiesis, but since no changes are observed in bone marrow hematopoietic cells or peripheral blood on a hemogram, it is believed that red pulp atrophy is not a change which indicates effects on hematopoietic functions. Therefore, based on this oral administration study in rats, it was judged that the lien should not be included in the specific target organs for repeated exposure. Moreover, according to Hagan et al's (1993) inhalation exposure test using rats, no effects on the lien were observed. Since the values in the other organs are within the guidance value ranges of "Category 2"in both species tests and no significant toxic effects have not been seen, it is proper to be classified as "Not classified" if based on GHS classification. Therefore, "Category 2 (lien)" of three-ministry GHS classification result is corrected to "Not classified".

Name: Acetophenone
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It is indicated that harmful effects were not seen in the 10000 ppm feeding administration test for 17 weeks using a rat (equivalent to about 500 mg/kg/day by a technical guide) (PATTY (5th, 2001) and ACGIH (2001)) and this dose exceeds the upper limit of the Category 2 guidance value range. Moreover, also in occupational exposure in humans, there is the statement that harmful effect is not reported (ACGIH (2001)). It was classified to outside of Category according to these things.

Name: Ethanaminium, 2-chloro-N,N,N-trimethyl-
Classification: Specific target organs/systemic toxicity following repeated exposure - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Because of the description of few toxic effects with dosage higher than the guidance value range of Category 2 in the subacute toxicity study with rats during 90 days, and of the mention of no toxic effect with dosage in the chronic toxicity study with rats for two years (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was judged out of Categories.

Name: Cyclohexanol
Rationale for classification: Not classified because of the dynamic viscosity: 24.6 mm2/s at 40ÂºC.

Name: chlorine trifluoride
Rationale for classification: Gas (GHS definition)

Name: Terephthalic Acid
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since it was suggested from 96-hour LC50>10mg/L of the fish (Oryzias Latipest) (MOE Eco-Toxicity Tests of Chemicals, 2002) that relevant toxicity is not indicated in the water solubility (15mg/L(PHYSPROP Database, 2005)) of this substance, it was classified into Not classified.

Name: Morpholine, 4-ethyl-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 72-hour ErC50>53mg/L of algae (Selenastrum) (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals, 2002).

Name: 1,3,5,7-Tetraazatricyclo[3.3.1.13.7]decane; Hexamethylenetetramine
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 48 hours EC50>100mg/L of the crustacea (Daphnia magna) (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals, 2002).

Name: Barium nitrate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 96 hours LC50=ca.1900mg/L of the fish (Gasterosteus Aculeatus) (IUCLID, 2000).

Name: Disulfur dichloride
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 96-hour LC50 >=3000mg/L of fishes (Zebrafish) (IUCLID, 2000).

Name: Boric acid
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 96 hours LC50=78.1mg boron/L(Boric Acid Equivalent: 447mg/L) of the fish (Rainbow Trout) (EHC204, 1998).

Name: Triethanolamine
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 96-hour ErC50=169mg/L of algae (Scenedesmus) (IUCLID, 2000).

Name: Bis(2-ehtylhexyl) adipate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since acute toxicity is not reported within the aqueous solubility concentrations (0.0032mg/L (SIDS (2002))), it was classified into Not classified.

Name: 2-(Diethylamino)ethyl methacrylate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 96 hours LC50>100mg/L of the fish (Oryzias Latipest) (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals (1997) and others.).

Name: epsilon-caprolactam
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 96 hours LC50>100mg/L of the fish (Oryzias Latipest) (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals (2001) and others.).

Name: Ethylene glycol
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 96 hours LC50>100mg/L of the fish (Oryzias Latipest) (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals (2001) and others.).

Name: 2,4-Pentanediol, 2-methyl-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 96-hour LC50>100 mg/L (MOE eco-toxicity tests of chemicals, 1997) of fishes (Oryzias latipes).

Name: Dibutyl phosphate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 96-hour LC50=110mg/L of fishes (Oryzias latipes) (SIDS, 2004).

Name: 2-Propanol, 1-methoxy-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 48-hour EC50>500mg/L of Crustacea (Daphnia magna)  (SIDS, 2003).

Name: Methyl isobutyl ketone
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 48-hour EC50=170mg/L of Crustacea  (Daphnia magna) (CERI Hazard Data, 2000).

Name: 2-Pentanol, 4-methyl-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 24-hour LC50=370mg/L of Crustacea (Brine shrimp) (IUCLID, 2000).

Name: 1-methylethyl acetate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It carried out the outside of Category from 48-hour LC50=110000microg/L of Crustacea (Brine shrimp) (AQUIRE, 2003).

Name: 2,4,6-Trichloro-1,3,5-triazine
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: It was classified into Not classified from 24 hours EC50>1000mg/L (the crustacea (Daphnia magna)) of cyanuric ester(hydrolysis product of this product) (SIDS (2005) and others.).

Name: Diisobutyl ketone
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (acute) - Not classified

Rationale for classification: Since rapidly degrading (BOD: 93.5% (existing chemical safety inspections data)), and less bio-accumulative (log Kow=0.41 (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)).

Name: Benzene, (trichloromethyl)-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since rapidly degrading (it hydrolyzed and benzoic acid and hydrochloric acid are generated (CERI Hazard Data, 2002)), and supposed less bio-accumulative (log Kow=3.9 (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)).

Name: Acetophenone
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since not water-insoluble (aqueous solubility = 6130 mg/L (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)) and acute toxicity is low.

Name: Benzene, (dichloromethyl)-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since rapidly degrading (BOD: 90% (existing chemical safety inspections data)), and less bio-accumulative (log Kow=2.97 (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)).

Name: Benzoyl chloride
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since rapidly degrading (it hydrolyzed and benzoic acid (BOD: 85%) is generated (Existing Chemicals Safety Check Data)), and supposed less bio-accumulative (log Kow=1.44 (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)).

Name: fosthiazate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since not water-insoluble (aqueous solubility = 9850mg/L(PHYSPROP Database, 2005)) and acute toxicity is low.

Name: 2-hydroxypropyl acrylate
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Since rapidly degrading (BOD: 61.3% (existing chemical safety inspections data)), and less bio-accumulative (log Kow=0.35 (PHYSPROP Database, 2005)).

Name: Ethanaminium, 2-chloro-N,N,N-trimethyl-
Classification: Hazardous to the aquatic environment (chronic) - Not classified
Rationale for classification: Based on NOEC=5 mg/L during 21 days of the shellfish (Daphnia magna) (IUCLID, 2000), though acute toxicity was Category 3.
